## What happened

In .NET 11, **Apple removed DSA support from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` (and all DSA sign/verify operations) now **throws at runtime on macOS only**. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two options:

**Option A — Avoid DSA on macOS entirely.** If you can re-sign your legacy data with a modern algorithm, migrate to **ECDsa** or **RSA**:

```csharp
// Replace DSA verification with ECDsa
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
ecdsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option B — Software fallback for legacy verification.** If you **must** verify existing DSA signatures (you can't re-sign), use a cross-platform software crypto library like **BouncyCastle** for DSA verification on macOS, while keeping the built-in path on Windows/Linux:

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    // Use BouncyCastle or another managed DSA implementation
}
else
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // existing verification code
}
```

**Recommendation:** If at all possible, go with **Option A** — re-sign with ECDsa/RSA and drop DSA entirely. DSA is a legacy algorithm across all platforms.
